    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="antithesis">I guess what I&apos;m saying is that methodological relativism does NOT imply a
struggle of all against all,</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="43" relname="span"> but precisley the opposite,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="25" relname="span"> everyone in their
own cheery worlds without having to talk to each other.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="42" relname="span"> &quot;Locality&quot; seems to
serve as this kind of &quot;good fences makes good neighbors&quot; buzzword.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="38" relname="background">

Compare for instance, Donald McCloskey&apos;s _The Rhetoric of Economics_ with
Philipp Mirowski&apos;s _More Heat Than Light_. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="30" relname="span"> McCloskey sticks to good old
symmetry and seems to dress down scientistic rhetoric.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="27" relname="antithesis">  Yet what his
admirerers seem to miss is the conclusion he seems to draw from it:</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="concession"> aw
shucks, sure economics is riddled with problems</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="27" relname="span"> but we&apos;re just folk here
after all.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="preparation"> So, implication:</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="26" relname="span"> DON&apos;T BOTHER US YOU CRITICS OF NEO-CLASSICAL
ECONOMICS,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="elaboration"> we have our own practical competence, ou &quot;local&quot; standards, blah,
blah, blah.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="30" relname="interpretation"> It is very unconstructivist in ignoring the differential,
institutional linkages with policy formations, etc.</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="15" relname="concession">

Poor old Mirowski, he is constructivist in this sense</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="32" relname="span"> but he strays from
symmetry.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="15" relname="elaboration"> He seems to be suggesting that economists misborrowed from
physicists in how they claimed to mathematicize utility and the like.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="33" relname="span">
Everyone knows you can&apos;t misborrow</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="17" relname="elaboration"> and you never want to compare one &quot;form
of life&quot; to another.</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="34" relname="span"> (A similar reaction can be found to Howe and Lyne&apos;s
critique of the use of evolutionary arguments in sociobiology:</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="36" relname="span"> the critics
(mostly) agree:</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="22" relname="condition"> if sociobiologists want to use evolution any old way they
like,</segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="35" relname="span"> no one can complain.)</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="40" relname="background"> (This debate was in _Social Epistemology_)</segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="41" relname="nonvolitional-result">

Is this what we wanted to get out of the critique of metanarratives?</segment>
